WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.500 --> 00:00:05.920
HUGH THOMPSON: Welcome,
everybody.

00:00:05.920 --> 00:00:08.109
Thanks so much for taking
the time to be here.

00:00:08.109 --> 00:00:08.800
I'm Hugh Thompson.

00:00:08.800 --> 00:00:10.210
BOB SULLIVAN: And I'm
Bob Sullivan.

00:00:10.210 --> 00:00:12.810
I've worked for NBC News
for almost 15 years.

00:00:12.810 --> 00:00:15.140
Most of that time I've spent
writing about technology and

00:00:15.140 --> 00:00:17.620
computer hackers and virus and
the computer underground.

00:00:17.620 --> 00:00:19.800
So I know a little bit
about this world.

00:00:19.800 --> 00:00:21.870
But in this building, I'm kind
of out of my league.

00:00:21.870 --> 00:00:23.160
So I'm going to turn
it over right away

00:00:23.160 --> 00:00:24.400
to Doctor Hugh Thompson.

00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:25.750
HUGH THOMPSON: Wow, man.

00:00:25.750 --> 00:00:26.245
Thanks.

00:00:26.245 --> 00:00:28.910
You usually don't show that
kind of deference.

00:00:28.910 --> 00:00:30.890
BOB SULLIVAN: I don't mean it.

00:00:30.890 --> 00:00:31.550
HUGH THOMPSON: Oh,
OK, all right.

00:00:31.550 --> 00:00:33.670
That makes me feel better.

00:00:33.670 --> 00:00:37.280
This book was a really
great journey for us.

00:00:37.280 --> 00:00:39.380
We ended up talking to a lot
of people in a lot of

00:00:39.380 --> 00:00:40.880
different diverse fields.

00:00:40.880 --> 00:00:42.370
And we'll spend some
time talking

00:00:42.370 --> 00:00:43.880
about the plateau effect.

00:00:43.880 --> 00:00:47.390
But to begin, I wanted to set
the stage with a personal

00:00:47.390 --> 00:00:49.090
plateau story.

00:00:49.090 --> 00:00:52.480
And so I've taught at Columbia
University for about five

00:00:52.480 --> 00:00:54.130
years, computer security.

00:00:54.130 --> 00:00:55.740
Many of my students
are at Google.

00:00:55.740 --> 00:00:59.170
So if anybody's out
there, hey.

00:00:59.170 --> 00:01:02.940
This happened, wow, I guess,
maybe 10 years ago.

00:01:02.940 --> 00:01:07.060
I was on a flight from Las Vegas
to Orlando which is a

00:01:07.060 --> 00:01:08.550
pretty long flight.

00:01:08.550 --> 00:01:11.270
And I brought my laptop there,
expected to get a

00:01:11.270 --> 00:01:12.640
bunch of work done.

00:01:12.640 --> 00:01:16.020
Two hours into the flight,
disaster happens, and I run

00:01:16.020 --> 00:01:17.280
out of battery.

00:01:17.280 --> 00:01:20.350
And I'm scrambling around,
figuring out what to do.

00:01:20.350 --> 00:01:23.200
Luckily, the plane had one
of these in-flight

00:01:23.200 --> 00:01:24.570
entertainment systems.

00:01:24.570 --> 00:01:26.440
How many people have ever
flown with one of these

00:01:26.440 --> 00:01:27.000
in-flight--

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:29.430
all right, yeah, pretty much
everybody has now.

00:01:29.430 --> 00:01:31.290
Back then they were
kind of unique.

00:01:31.290 --> 00:01:32.600
And so I pull this thing up.

00:01:32.600 --> 00:01:34.560
Oprah's got a terrible
guest on.

00:01:34.560 --> 00:01:36.980
Doctor Phil I just can't do.

00:01:36.980 --> 00:01:40.290
And, finally, I turn my
attention to the games.

00:01:40.290 --> 00:01:43.230
And these are incredibly
cheesy games.

00:01:43.230 --> 00:01:45.720
I don't know if you've ever
played any of these things.

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:50.080
And one looks strikingly
similar to the classic

00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:54.040
strategy game Tetris but
was called [? Fatris ?]

00:01:54.040 --> 00:01:56.020
I guess for copyright reasons.

00:01:56.020 --> 00:01:58.010
So I pull this thing up.

00:01:58.010 --> 00:02:01.270
And I'm playing for a while,
and I'm a pretty advanced

00:02:01.270 --> 00:02:02.780
Tetris player.

00:02:02.780 --> 00:02:05.590
I'm sure I'm not alone
in this crowd.

00:02:05.590 --> 00:02:10.080
And so I went to the options
configuration screen which was

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:14.060
ambitiously worded because
it was only one option.

00:02:14.060 --> 00:02:18.620
And the option was how many
blocks would you like to see

00:02:18.620 --> 00:02:19.760
in advance?

00:02:19.760 --> 00:02:21.620
So for anybody's who has played
Tetris, you know the

00:02:21.620 --> 00:02:23.930
more blocks you can see in
advance before they come, you

00:02:23.930 --> 00:02:26.540
can plan because you're waiting
on that big four block

00:02:26.540 --> 00:02:28.450
line to come down.

00:02:28.450 --> 00:02:32.170
So it had a touch screen
control, a plus-minus control

00:02:32.170 --> 00:02:33.260
on the screen.

00:02:33.260 --> 00:02:35.090
And I keep hitting plus.

00:02:35.090 --> 00:02:37.550
And the maximum value
that this thing

00:02:37.550 --> 00:02:39.170
would take was four.

00:02:39.170 --> 00:02:39.460
Right.

00:02:39.460 --> 00:02:41.040
So that's the maximum number
of blocks that

00:02:41.040 --> 00:02:42.410
you can see in advance.

00:02:42.410 --> 00:02:44.870
And so I asked the question I'm
sure any of you would have

00:02:44.870 --> 00:02:49.520
asked in a similar circumstance,
what can I do to

00:02:49.520 --> 00:02:53.350
increment this value
beyond four?

00:02:53.350 --> 00:02:56.160
Again, I had an hour
left on the flight.

00:02:56.160 --> 00:02:59.920
And so I noticed that there was
a phone console attached

00:02:59.920 --> 00:03:01.840
to this in-flight entertainment
system.

00:03:01.840 --> 00:03:05.180
You know you swipe your credit
card and make $23 a minute

00:03:05.180 --> 00:03:06.840
calls to friends and family.

00:03:06.840 --> 00:03:10.100
So I picked this thing up and
I see that it's connected to

00:03:10.100 --> 00:03:11.740
this entertainment system.

00:03:11.740 --> 00:03:13.556
So I select the four.

00:03:13.556 --> 00:03:16.210
I kind of hold it down,
it gets highlighted.

00:03:16.210 --> 00:03:18.460
And I try and type in 10.

00:03:18.460 --> 00:03:21.410
Very disappointing, it changed
to one and then it

00:03:21.410 --> 00:03:22.340
changed to a 0.

00:03:22.340 --> 00:03:24.430
Both of which are
legal values.

00:03:24.430 --> 00:03:26.960
And so then I thought, OK, well,
maybe there's a single

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:28.330
digit constraint here.

00:03:28.330 --> 00:03:30.000
So I tried an eight.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:30.835
Again, very disappointing.

00:03:30.835 --> 00:03:32.650
It didn't do anything.

00:03:32.650 --> 00:03:37.430
So then I thought OK, one of
the most common errors in

00:03:37.430 --> 00:03:39.470
coding is to be off by one.

00:03:39.470 --> 00:03:39.820
Right?

00:03:39.820 --> 00:03:42.460
So you're meant to write the
code that says this value

00:03:42.460 --> 00:03:45.440
shall be less than five, but you
accidentally write, this

00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:47.600
value shall be less than
or equal to five.

00:03:47.600 --> 00:03:49.460
Boundary value testing.

00:03:49.460 --> 00:03:53.660
So I put in a five,
and it took it.

00:03:53.660 --> 00:03:56.200
And I'm sitting there, it's the
most excited I think I've

00:03:56.200 --> 00:03:59.160
ever been on a plane.

00:03:59.160 --> 00:04:03.360
I go back to the touch screen
control, and I hit plus, and

00:04:03.360 --> 00:04:04.610
it increments to six.

00:04:07.600 --> 00:04:11.540
Now my guess is the logic around
the plus control said

00:04:11.540 --> 00:04:14.380
something like if four
do not increment.

00:04:14.380 --> 00:04:15.290
Well, it wasn't four.

00:04:15.290 --> 00:04:16.140
It was five.

00:04:16.140 --> 00:04:16.660
So it happily went up.

00:04:16.660 --> 00:04:18.339
So I'm sitting there in the
chair, pulse, pulse, pulse,

00:04:18.339 --> 00:04:23.750
pulse, pulse, pulse, pulse,
until I get to 127 and pause

00:04:23.750 --> 00:04:25.550
for a moment of reflection.

00:04:25.550 --> 00:04:30.190
Now 127 is a number very near
and dear to my heart as I'm

00:04:30.190 --> 00:04:31.840
sure it is for many of you.

00:04:31.840 --> 00:04:35.730
It's the upper band of a single
byte signed integer.

00:04:35.730 --> 00:04:38.792
And so normal math, and my PhD
is in math so I can attest to

00:04:38.792 --> 00:04:42.580
this, says that 127
plus 1 equals 128.

00:04:42.580 --> 00:04:47.510
But sometimes 127 plus 1 equals,
anybody remember?

00:04:47.510 --> 00:04:48.800
Negative 128.

00:04:48.800 --> 00:04:48.990
Right?

00:04:48.990 --> 00:04:51.710
It will wrap around to the
most negative value.

00:04:51.710 --> 00:04:53.860
So I think about this
for a second and

00:04:53.860 --> 00:04:55.230
consider where I am.

00:04:55.230 --> 00:04:56.960
BOB SULLIVAN: 30,000
feet in the air.

00:04:56.960 --> 00:04:57.820
HUGH THOMPSON: 33,000.

00:04:57.820 --> 00:04:58.610
BOB SULLIVAN: Sorry.

00:04:58.610 --> 00:05:01.350
HUGH THOMPSON: Don't
undersell it.

00:05:01.350 --> 00:05:05.460
But in the name of science,
I hit plus one more time.

00:05:05.460 --> 00:05:09.170
The screen flashes negative
128 just for a second.

00:05:09.170 --> 00:05:12.340
And then, proof, screen
goes black.

00:05:12.340 --> 00:05:12.900
Proof.

00:05:12.900 --> 00:05:16.200
Guy's screen next to
me goes black.

00:05:16.200 --> 00:05:19.590
The entire plane entertainment
system goes down.

00:05:19.590 --> 00:05:22.110
And I'm sitting like this
in the chair hoping that

00:05:22.110 --> 00:05:24.180
something doesn't go
off to the left.

00:05:24.180 --> 00:05:27.580
Now it's interesting to
think about this.

00:05:27.580 --> 00:05:30.570
And as somebody who's done a lot
of software testing, and

00:05:30.570 --> 00:05:33.070
I've written a bunch of books
on secure coding, a book

00:05:33.070 --> 00:05:34.680
called "How To Break Software
Security," a

00:05:34.680 --> 00:05:36.860
software testing book.

00:05:36.860 --> 00:05:38.970
That is the first time
that I ever ran

00:05:38.970 --> 00:05:40.420
into the plateau effect.

00:05:40.420 --> 00:05:44.150
If you sit a tester down and
say, I need you to break this.

00:05:44.150 --> 00:05:45.680
I need you to find bugs.

00:05:45.680 --> 00:05:48.230
You find a lot of bugs right
at the beginning.

00:05:48.230 --> 00:05:52.340
And then quickly your rate of
bug finding plateaus off.

00:05:52.340 --> 00:05:55.690
It turns out that that plateau
curve, like the natural

00:05:55.690 --> 00:06:00.270
logarithm, shows up in almost
every area of our lives.

00:06:00.270 --> 00:06:03.350
And that's what the plateau
effect is about.

00:06:03.350 --> 00:06:07.411
Why do you sometimes
get more for less?

00:06:07.411 --> 00:06:10.155
BOB SULLIVAN: So I have not
broken any airplane's

00:06:10.155 --> 00:06:11.600
in-flight entertainment
system.

00:06:11.600 --> 00:06:12.450
HUGH THOMPSON: Good.

00:06:12.450 --> 00:06:12.600
Good.

00:06:12.600 --> 00:06:14.150
It's like a support meeting.

00:06:14.150 --> 00:06:14.870
BOB SULLIVAN: Yet, yet.

00:06:14.870 --> 00:06:15.620
I have an excellent
trainer, though.

00:06:15.620 --> 00:06:16.410
HUGH THOMPSON: Don't
do it, man.

00:06:16.410 --> 00:06:17.800
I strongly advise against it.

00:06:17.800 --> 00:06:20.220
BOB SULLIVAN: So what was the
odds-- somewhere in your brain

00:06:20.220 --> 00:06:22.500
you thought, is this
plane going down?

00:06:22.500 --> 00:06:23.400
HUGH THOMPSON: Oh,
no it's not.

00:06:23.400 --> 00:06:23.900
It wasn't.

00:06:23.900 --> 00:06:25.700
I had faith in the--

00:06:25.700 --> 00:06:27.980
BOB SULLIVAN: So the point of
the testing story is that,

00:06:27.980 --> 00:06:30.220
again, if you keep doing the
same kind of things over and

00:06:30.220 --> 00:06:32.710
over again your returns
get less and less.

00:06:32.710 --> 00:06:34.280
And we all know those people
who have ever tried to lose

00:06:34.280 --> 00:06:38.060
weight or body build are very
familiar with what the concept

00:06:38.060 --> 00:06:39.160
of the plateau effect is.

00:06:39.160 --> 00:06:40.560
It hits testing.

00:06:40.560 --> 00:06:42.570
It hits people who try learning
to play the piano.

00:06:42.570 --> 00:06:43.530
It hits marriages.

00:06:43.530 --> 00:06:45.000
It hits businesses.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:47.120
Things that you do that were
formally effective suddenly

00:06:47.120 --> 00:06:48.860
become less and less
effective.

00:06:48.860 --> 00:06:50.910
So in testing, for example,
it's a really good answer.

00:06:50.910 --> 00:06:53.040
Testers have come up with a
spectacular answer for this

00:06:53.040 --> 00:06:54.390
which is fuzzing.

00:06:54.390 --> 00:06:56.810
So instead of hiring testers,
you hire piano players.

00:06:56.810 --> 00:06:58.470
You hire random people
off the street.

00:06:58.470 --> 00:06:59.760
And they do unexpected things.

00:06:59.760 --> 00:07:02.030
And those unexpected things are
actually what break you

00:07:02.030 --> 00:07:03.000
through this plateau.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:04.300
But the problem is,
and it's funny--

00:07:04.300 --> 00:07:05.800
I just met with an
old colleague.

00:07:05.800 --> 00:07:08.130
I can't say who he was, but
he is the head of a very

00:07:08.130 --> 00:07:10.060
important news organization.

00:07:10.060 --> 00:07:12.030
And we were talking about how
when you stay at the same

00:07:12.030 --> 00:07:14.860
place for 20 years or more, it's
a lot more like you're

00:07:14.860 --> 00:07:16.470
running on a treadmill
instead of running

00:07:16.470 --> 00:07:17.660
out in the real world.

00:07:17.660 --> 00:07:19.090
And you can get very, very
good at running on a

00:07:19.090 --> 00:07:21.030
treadmill, you can
be the world's

00:07:21.030 --> 00:07:22.180
fastest treadmill runner.

00:07:22.180 --> 00:07:23.490
But that doesn't mean you're
going to be any good at

00:07:23.490 --> 00:07:24.800
running in the real world.

00:07:24.800 --> 00:07:27.640
So that's the problem with doing
the same thing over and

00:07:27.640 --> 00:07:28.080
over again.

00:07:28.080 --> 00:07:29.946
It ceases to work.

00:07:29.946 --> 00:07:34.090
HUGH THOMPSON: And it's
incredible, this curve, and,

00:07:34.090 --> 00:07:37.000
again, you can think of this,
well, natural log

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:38.070
is similar to this.

00:07:38.070 --> 00:07:41.190
But this curve pops
up in almost every

00:07:41.190 --> 00:07:43.170
area of human endeavor.

00:07:43.170 --> 00:07:45.840
If you're in medicine, for
example, this looks like the

00:07:45.840 --> 00:07:47.540
dose response curve.

00:07:47.540 --> 00:07:49.400
The point at which
medicine becomes

00:07:49.400 --> 00:07:51.890
ineffective as doses increase.

00:07:51.890 --> 00:07:54.480
If you look at somebody who's
trying to lose weight, for

00:07:54.480 --> 00:07:56.400
example, same thing happens.

00:07:56.400 --> 00:07:58.100
They plateau off.

00:07:58.100 --> 00:08:02.700
So this curve, we spent three
years talking to people in

00:08:02.700 --> 00:08:07.590
psychology, medicine, venture
capital, folks even as diverse

00:08:07.590 --> 00:08:10.720
as cooks and culinary artists,
I didn't realize they were

00:08:10.720 --> 00:08:12.300
called artists.

00:08:12.300 --> 00:08:17.900
And this same curve shows up
over and over and over again.

00:08:17.900 --> 00:08:21.180
So the question that the book
tries to answer is are there

00:08:21.180 --> 00:08:24.000
commonalities to plateaus?

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:27.590
Are there sets of underlying
conditions, causes that are

00:08:27.590 --> 00:08:30.950
the same if you're trying to
break a piece of software or

00:08:30.950 --> 00:08:33.280
you're trying to lose weight
or you're trying to start a

00:08:33.280 --> 00:08:34.830
business or you're trying
to get your

00:08:34.830 --> 00:08:37.200
business to the next level?

00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:39.630
And we spent, like I said, about
three years trying to

00:08:39.630 --> 00:08:40.809
answer this question.

00:08:40.809 --> 00:08:42.549
And we found that there
are these eight

00:08:42.549 --> 00:08:46.570
causal factors of plateaus.

00:08:46.570 --> 00:08:50.010
But talk about the book scene
and where it starts.

00:08:50.010 --> 00:08:52.190
BOB SULLIVAN: So before we
tell you what the eight

00:08:52.190 --> 00:08:54.040
factors are, we want to give you
another example of what a

00:08:54.040 --> 00:08:55.740
plateau is like.

00:08:55.740 --> 00:08:57.770
I'm sure some of you have spent
some time in your life

00:08:57.770 --> 00:08:59.310
in the Bay Area, here.

00:08:59.310 --> 00:09:00.440
Right?

00:09:00.440 --> 00:09:02.590
Have any of you eaten at this
restaurant, The Stinking Rose?

00:09:02.590 --> 00:09:03.630
You all familiar with it?

00:09:03.630 --> 00:09:06.740
The Stinking Rose is probably
the most famous garlic

00:09:06.740 --> 00:09:08.680
restaurant, maybe even
in the world.

00:09:08.680 --> 00:09:08.870
Right?

00:09:08.870 --> 00:09:10.530
Everything on the
menu is garlic.

00:09:10.530 --> 00:09:12.010
They have garlic ice cream.

00:09:12.010 --> 00:09:16.320
The Stinking Rose, well,
stinks of garlic.

00:09:16.320 --> 00:09:18.800
You can smell it
down the block.

00:09:18.800 --> 00:09:22.080
The most overpowering sensory
experience you might have ever

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:25.080
with your nose is walking
into The Stinking Rose.

00:09:25.080 --> 00:09:27.010
And you walk in, they sit you
at your table, you sit down,

00:09:27.010 --> 00:09:28.590
they hand you a menu.

00:09:28.590 --> 00:09:31.190
And what happens to that garlic
smell as you sit there

00:09:31.190 --> 00:09:33.540
looking at the menu?

00:09:33.540 --> 00:09:34.895
It disappears.

00:09:34.895 --> 00:09:36.620
It's gone.

00:09:36.620 --> 00:09:37.890
Did the garlic all go away?

00:09:37.890 --> 00:09:38.140
No.

00:09:38.140 --> 00:09:39.570
Your nose just stopped
smelling it.

00:09:39.570 --> 00:09:42.430
Your nose got what's
called acclimated.

00:09:42.430 --> 00:09:45.480
Acclimation is a part of
all of our biologies.

00:09:45.480 --> 00:09:46.530
It's built into us.

00:09:46.530 --> 00:09:47.940
Our bodies are literally
designed

00:09:47.940 --> 00:09:49.810
to ignore the familiar.

00:09:49.810 --> 00:09:52.710
So even something as powerful as
a garlic-filled restaurant

00:09:52.710 --> 00:09:55.740
suddenly becomes familiar and
effectively disappears from

00:09:55.740 --> 00:09:56.950
your consciousness.

00:09:56.950 --> 00:09:58.270
That's the power
of acclimation.

00:09:58.270 --> 00:10:00.800
And acclimation is one of the
main causes, one of the first

00:10:00.800 --> 00:10:02.560
causes of a plateau.

00:10:02.560 --> 00:10:04.730
We get used to things
that are familiar.

00:10:04.730 --> 00:10:08.240
And slowly but surely our
sensory experience of them

00:10:08.240 --> 00:10:09.440
disappears.

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:11.990
If you actually plot acclimation
on a graph from

00:10:11.990 --> 00:10:14.600
your nasal olfactory nerves,
it follows that

00:10:14.600 --> 00:10:16.110
plateau curve exactly.

00:10:16.110 --> 00:10:18.450
So anyone who's ever experienced
walking into a

00:10:18.450 --> 00:10:20.200
locker room and saying,
oh this is horrible.

00:10:20.200 --> 00:10:22.750
And then suddenly
you can bear it.

00:10:22.750 --> 00:10:25.500
Then you know precisely what
the plateau is and why your

00:10:25.500 --> 00:10:28.270
body is actually working against
you so that whatever

00:10:28.270 --> 00:10:30.790
you do every day, you slowly
but surely get

00:10:30.790 --> 00:10:32.381
less good at it.

00:10:32.381 --> 00:10:34.720
HUGH THOMPSON: Yeah, thank
goodness for that plateau.

00:10:34.720 --> 00:10:37.290
By the way, mention Bob and Hugh
at The Stinking Rose for

00:10:37.290 --> 00:10:38.826
a 10% discount.

00:10:38.826 --> 00:10:40.310
No, just kidding.

00:10:40.310 --> 00:10:41.740
Actually, we should
set that up.

00:10:41.740 --> 00:10:42.470
BOB SULLIVAN: That's
a really good idea.

00:10:42.470 --> 00:10:42.800
Marketing.

00:10:42.800 --> 00:10:46.460
HUGH THOMPSON: So what is
the plateau effect?

00:10:46.460 --> 00:10:49.620
Essentially, it's the law
of diminishing returns.

00:10:49.620 --> 00:10:53.050
We get less and less for
applying the same thing over

00:10:53.050 --> 00:10:53.750
and over again.

00:10:53.750 --> 00:10:56.080
But it's more than just that.

00:10:56.080 --> 00:11:00.730
I think if you don't know that
the plateau effect exists in a

00:11:00.730 --> 00:11:03.280
particular pursuit,
you give up.

00:11:03.280 --> 00:11:04.800
You think that you've
peaked out.

00:11:04.800 --> 00:11:05.830
You've topped off.

00:11:05.830 --> 00:11:09.360
It's the maximum amount that you
can ever get out of this

00:11:09.360 --> 00:11:10.750
particular endeavor.

00:11:10.750 --> 00:11:14.640
I'm just thinking about the
shift in testing that happened

00:11:14.640 --> 00:11:18.130
when we went from free form
exploratory testing and

00:11:18.130 --> 00:11:20.780
automated testing
over to fuzzing.

00:11:20.780 --> 00:11:22.740
So, of course, we
still do both.

00:11:22.740 --> 00:11:26.290
But if you look at most of
the major vulnerabilities

00:11:26.290 --> 00:11:29.920
discovered in software today,
they're found by fuzzing.

00:11:29.920 --> 00:11:33.890
And fuzzing is like an
amphetamine-laden monkey,

00:11:33.890 --> 00:11:37.230
right, that you just kind of sat
off in front of a keyboard

00:11:37.230 --> 00:11:39.810
and hoped for the best
and see what happens.

00:11:39.810 --> 00:11:41.940
It's because systems
are so complex.

00:11:41.940 --> 00:11:45.630
It's very difficult sometimes
to reason through the exact

00:11:45.630 --> 00:11:48.250
set of inputs that may
cause it to fail.

00:11:48.250 --> 00:11:51.680
That idea of applying diversity,
or fuzzing, to

00:11:51.680 --> 00:11:57.170
other areas of your life has,
we found, applied in things

00:11:57.170 --> 00:12:00.380
like weight loss, things
like muscle building.

00:12:00.380 --> 00:12:02.130
I don't know if anybody
here has ever tried

00:12:02.130 --> 00:12:03.970
cross fit, for example.

00:12:03.970 --> 00:12:06.900
But the whole premise of cross
fit is based on fuzzing.

00:12:06.900 --> 00:12:10.730
Doing different things every
single day to try and get your

00:12:10.730 --> 00:12:14.380
body surprised or shocked
into change.

00:12:14.380 --> 00:12:17.150
So we mentioned these eight
elements of plateaus.

00:12:17.150 --> 00:12:19.490
We won't have time to go
into all of them today.

00:12:19.490 --> 00:12:20.760
That's what the book is for.

00:12:20.760 --> 00:12:22.850
And the book is much longer.

00:12:22.850 --> 00:12:25.500
Or the audio book which
is only eight hours.

00:12:25.500 --> 00:12:27.820
So consider that for
your weekend.

00:12:27.820 --> 00:12:30.700
It's a denial of weekend
attack--

00:12:30.700 --> 00:12:33.270
DOW, DOW.

00:12:33.270 --> 00:12:37.310
Or you can listen to two,
and then it's a DDOW.

00:12:37.310 --> 00:12:40.240
But these are the eight
causes that we found.

00:12:40.240 --> 00:12:43.370
You see immunity as the
base at the bottom.

00:12:43.370 --> 00:12:45.950
And I think that there's a
threat of immunity that goes

00:12:45.950 --> 00:12:47.050
through all of these.

00:12:47.050 --> 00:12:50.530
We just naturally get used
to certain stimulus.

00:12:50.530 --> 00:12:53.480
And we talked about
immunity already.

00:12:53.480 --> 00:12:56.070
We talked about it in
the testing space.

00:12:56.070 --> 00:13:01.690
We found that immunity is such
a common cause of plateaus in

00:13:01.690 --> 00:13:05.500
other areas of our life like
sports, for example.

00:13:05.500 --> 00:13:08.515
Still, that Derek Jeter
thing shocks me.

