00:15:51.190 --> 00:15:52.880
HUGH THOMPSON: The
second element

00:15:52.880 --> 00:15:54.510
is the greedy algorithm.

00:15:54.510 --> 00:15:57.140
Anybody here that has ever
studied math has run into the

00:15:57.140 --> 00:15:58.140
greedy algorithm.

00:15:58.140 --> 00:16:03.140
It basically says we take the
locally optimal solution.

00:16:03.140 --> 00:16:06.020
So whenever seems like the place
that we make the most

00:16:06.020 --> 00:16:08.200
progress immediately we take.

00:16:08.200 --> 00:16:11.050
And we have a scene in the
book where we talk about,

00:16:11.050 --> 00:16:13.060
because Bob and I have suffered
through this so many

00:16:13.060 --> 00:16:16.440
times, you've got to get
20 blocks in Manhattan,

00:16:16.440 --> 00:16:17.670
how do you do it?

00:16:17.670 --> 00:16:20.510
Well, somebody who's following
the greedy algorithm says, OK,

00:16:20.510 --> 00:16:23.430
look, I probably have to wait
two minutes to flag down a

00:16:23.430 --> 00:16:25.050
cab, and during those
two minutes,

00:16:25.050 --> 00:16:26.860
I'm making zero progress.

00:16:26.860 --> 00:16:29.810
Or I could go to the subway stop
which might be two blocks

00:16:29.810 --> 00:16:31.130
in the wrong direction.

00:16:31.130 --> 00:16:33.440
In that case, I'm making
negative progress.

00:16:33.440 --> 00:16:35.310
I'm getting further and further
away from where I'm

00:16:35.310 --> 00:16:36.380
supposed to go.

00:16:36.380 --> 00:16:39.150
Or if you're following the
greedy algorithm, you just

00:16:39.150 --> 00:16:40.370
start walking.

00:16:40.370 --> 00:16:43.390
Because instantly you're making
immediate progress.

00:16:43.390 --> 00:16:47.570
If somebody looked at you a
minute after you began this

00:16:47.570 --> 00:16:51.950
quest, the person who started
walking towards the goal looks

00:16:51.950 --> 00:16:53.540
like he's made progress.

00:16:53.540 --> 00:16:55.560
He's getting closer.

00:16:55.560 --> 00:16:58.220
But everybody who's ever lived
in New York knows that the

00:16:58.220 --> 00:17:02.380
fastest way to get anywhere,
most of the time, well,

00:17:02.380 --> 00:17:04.589
fingers crossed,
is the subway.

00:17:04.589 --> 00:17:07.910
And the subway often requires
you to make something that we

00:17:07.910 --> 00:17:09.829
call retrograde progress.

00:17:09.829 --> 00:17:12.890
Sometimes you have to go in
completely the opposite

00:17:12.890 --> 00:17:15.910
direction to make a bigger
leap forward.

00:17:15.910 --> 00:17:19.420
It turns out that the greedy
algorithm occurs all the time

00:17:19.420 --> 00:17:20.660
in other areas too.

00:17:20.660 --> 00:17:23.410
In business, we see it
happen all the time.

00:17:23.410 --> 00:17:27.020
Publicly traded companies,
they're subject to 90 day

00:17:27.020 --> 00:17:30.360
windows of performance when
earnings come out.

00:17:30.360 --> 00:17:34.400
So if you're a publicly traded
company, you have to follow

00:17:34.400 --> 00:17:37.170
the 90 day window greedy
algorithm.

00:17:37.170 --> 00:17:39.770
You have to optimize
for profit.

00:17:39.770 --> 00:17:42.620
You have to optimize for revenue
during that period

00:17:42.620 --> 00:17:46.000
even though that may not be in
the best interest of the long

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.140
term health of the company.

00:17:48.140 --> 00:17:52.330
So this greedy algorithm we
found is a very common reason

00:17:52.330 --> 00:17:53.640
why people reach plateau.

00:17:57.197 --> 00:17:59.520
BOB SULLIVAN: Meanwhile, timing
is also a very, very

00:17:59.520 --> 00:18:00.480
important issue.

00:18:00.480 --> 00:18:02.820
And timing gets into our lives,
of course, you can

00:18:02.820 --> 00:18:04.120
think of comedic timing.

00:18:04.120 --> 00:18:05.220
You can think of a
good time to have

00:18:05.220 --> 00:18:06.120
children in your family.

00:18:06.120 --> 00:18:10.300
You can think of a good time to
book some sales so you can

00:18:10.300 --> 00:18:11.870
pump up your quarterly
numbers.

00:18:11.870 --> 00:18:14.790
But timing is a really
interesting element.

00:18:14.790 --> 00:18:16.800
This is a really interesting
time for time right now in

00:18:16.800 --> 00:18:17.980
human history.

00:18:17.980 --> 00:18:21.180
We spent a lot of time with a
group called the Quantified

00:18:21.180 --> 00:18:22.300
Self Movement in the book.

00:18:22.300 --> 00:18:24.900
Has anybody here heard of the
Quantified Self Movement.

00:18:24.900 --> 00:18:26.020
HUGH THOMPSON: Have you ever
been to a meeting?

00:18:26.020 --> 00:18:27.260
Has anybody here ever
been to a meeting?

00:18:27.260 --> 00:18:28.010
Just out of curiosity.

00:18:28.010 --> 00:18:28.265
OK.

00:18:28.265 --> 00:18:30.210
BOB SULLIVAN: There are
chapters of Quantified

00:18:30.210 --> 00:18:33.420
Selfers, they are called QSers,
all over the world.

00:18:33.420 --> 00:18:34.990
One of the largest is actually
in New York.

00:18:34.990 --> 00:18:35.390
They are in Brooklyn.

00:18:35.390 --> 00:18:37.110
And so we went to a couple
of their meetings

00:18:37.110 --> 00:18:38.190
and got to know them.

00:18:38.190 --> 00:18:40.820
These are people who watch
what you guys do.

00:18:40.820 --> 00:18:42.240
You guys are counting
everything, observing

00:18:42.240 --> 00:18:46.120
everything that we do, big data
about the world, studying

00:18:46.120 --> 00:18:47.920
it, maximizing efficiencies.

00:18:47.920 --> 00:18:50.020
And they're doing that
about themselves.

00:18:50.020 --> 00:18:52.880
So these people in the world
of a million little sensors

00:18:52.880 --> 00:18:55.550
that are all connected, they
put sensors on their body.

00:18:55.550 --> 00:18:56.960
They put sensors
on their wrist.

00:18:56.960 --> 00:18:58.570
And they count how many breaths
they take during the

00:18:58.570 --> 00:19:01.390
day, what their heart rate is
every five seconds or over the

00:19:01.390 --> 00:19:02.640
course of an entire day.

00:19:02.640 --> 00:19:04.470
They plot their oxygen intake.

00:19:04.470 --> 00:19:07.150
And then they measure that
against things like what kind

00:19:07.150 --> 00:19:08.070
of a mood am I in?

00:19:08.070 --> 00:19:09.280
How well did I run?

00:19:09.280 --> 00:19:11.520
A lot of them are performance
related.

00:19:11.520 --> 00:19:12.900
A lot of them are runners
in particular.

00:19:12.900 --> 00:19:15.220
And if you talk to any of them,
they will tell you, I

00:19:15.220 --> 00:19:17.520
know that the best time for me
to start a five mile run is

00:19:17.520 --> 00:19:20.060
exactly at 7:37 in the
morning when it's

00:19:20.060 --> 00:19:22.670
between 60 and 65 degrees.

00:19:22.670 --> 00:19:26.320
Now, a lot of this feels like
they're just enhancing their

00:19:26.320 --> 00:19:28.670
own OCD tendencies.

00:19:28.670 --> 00:19:30.650
HUGH THOMPSON: They were in
better shape than we were.

00:19:30.650 --> 00:19:31.350
BOB SULLIVAN: They were
in much better shape.

00:19:31.350 --> 00:19:32.850
It was a very intimidating
room to be in.

00:19:32.850 --> 00:19:33.610
Let me tell you.

00:19:33.610 --> 00:19:33.935
Yeah

00:19:33.935 --> 00:19:36.565
HUGH THOMPSON: It's
on a high bar.

00:19:36.565 --> 00:19:39.950
BOB SULLIVAN: But this might
seem extreme right now.

00:19:39.950 --> 00:19:41.610
But a lot of this is becoming
more and more popular.

00:19:41.610 --> 00:19:44.690
There's a whole technology now
called slumber tech where

00:19:44.690 --> 00:19:47.310
people are attaching devices to
themselves and doing what

00:19:47.310 --> 00:19:49.400
only high-end hospitals used
to do, which is seeing what

00:19:49.400 --> 00:19:50.300
kind of a sleep am I getting.

00:19:50.300 --> 00:19:51.990
How much REM sleep
am I getting?

00:19:51.990 --> 00:19:54.870
You attach something to your
wrist, or you wear a shirt

00:19:54.870 --> 00:19:56.470
that attaches to an iPhone.

00:19:56.470 --> 00:19:58.450
It downloads to a website which
then in a week or two

00:19:58.450 --> 00:20:00.540
analyzes whether or not you
need to sleep more.

00:20:00.540 --> 00:20:05.060
So we are actually starting
to get a grasp on time and

00:20:05.060 --> 00:20:06.710
figuring out is this
a good time or a

00:20:06.710 --> 00:20:08.200
bad time to do things?

00:20:08.200 --> 00:20:11.890
Now, timing, of course, has been
this human quest forever.

00:20:11.890 --> 00:20:14.500
But a lot of people have
studied time in these

00:20:14.500 --> 00:20:16.370
incredibly detailed ways.

00:20:16.370 --> 00:20:18.890
And the one that we talk about
a lot in the book, because

00:20:18.890 --> 00:20:21.270
there's a good time and a bad
time for things, is in

00:20:21.270 --> 00:20:22.550
memorization.

00:20:22.550 --> 00:20:24.035
So do you want to talk about
memorization, or do you want

00:20:24.035 --> 00:20:24.800
me to go ahead?

00:20:24.800 --> 00:20:25.250
HUGH THOMPSON: Yeah.

00:20:25.250 --> 00:20:25.510
Yeah.

00:20:25.510 --> 00:20:25.850
Sure.

00:20:25.850 --> 00:20:25.905
Go.

00:20:25.905 --> 00:20:26.230
Go.

00:20:26.230 --> 00:20:26.970
BOB SULLIVAN: We can
talk about this.

00:20:26.970 --> 00:20:29.730
And so the Ebbinghaus Spacing
Effect, which maybe some of

00:20:29.730 --> 00:20:33.150
you encountered in your studies,
says basically this,

00:20:33.150 --> 00:20:36.010
ever since we were little kids,
we were told there's one

00:20:36.010 --> 00:20:38.410
way to learn multiplication
tables.

00:20:38.410 --> 00:20:39.690
Beat it into your head.

00:20:39.690 --> 00:20:41.460
Repetition over and
over again.

00:20:41.460 --> 00:20:44.290
And if you went to a modern
school in the last 20 years or

00:20:44.290 --> 00:20:46.300
so they might have said,
repetition is horrible.

00:20:46.300 --> 00:20:47.110
It beats kids up.

00:20:47.110 --> 00:20:47.580
It's no good.

00:20:47.580 --> 00:20:50.580
So there's this rote
memorization, anti-rote

00:20:50.580 --> 00:20:51.480
memorization school.

00:20:51.480 --> 00:20:53.920
And of course both of them are
wrong and ineffective.

00:20:53.920 --> 00:20:56.730
But what we have found
and what [? Henrik ?]

00:20:56.730 --> 00:21:01.140
Ebbinghaus found 100 years ago
is that it's not repeating

00:21:01.140 --> 00:21:03.610
something over and over again,
it's when you repeat it.

00:21:03.610 --> 00:21:07.630
So there's this very specific
curve which suggests that

00:21:07.630 --> 00:21:09.450
constant repetition
becomes very, very

00:21:09.450 --> 00:21:10.400
ineffective very quickly.

00:21:10.400 --> 00:21:12.330
You could sit down, I'm sure
you've had this experience,

00:21:12.330 --> 00:21:13.570
you meet someone at a party.

00:21:13.570 --> 00:21:14.600
His name is Bob.

00:21:14.600 --> 00:21:15.180
His name is Bob.

00:21:15.180 --> 00:21:15.370
His name is Bob.

00:21:15.370 --> 00:21:15.670
I'm going to remember.

00:21:15.670 --> 00:21:17.010
Bob, Bob, Bob, Bob.

00:21:17.010 --> 00:21:17.985
His name is Bob.

00:21:17.985 --> 00:21:19.890
Oh, Hugh, how you doing?

00:21:19.890 --> 00:21:21.430
What was that guy's name?

00:21:21.430 --> 00:21:23.200
It happens constantly, right?

00:21:23.200 --> 00:21:26.420
And it's because it's not
effective to repeat it over

00:21:26.420 --> 00:21:27.510
and over again.

00:21:27.510 --> 00:21:30.650
But it turns out, if you start
to forget something and then

00:21:30.650 --> 00:21:34.070
you remind yourself of that, you
pop it up to the surface

00:21:34.070 --> 00:21:34.590
of your memory.

00:21:34.590 --> 00:21:36.500
And then you do it again.

00:21:36.500 --> 00:21:37.220
And then you do it again.

00:21:37.220 --> 00:21:39.070
And if you do it at these very
in particular spaced

00:21:39.070 --> 00:21:40.780
repetitions, they are different
for everybody, but

00:21:40.780 --> 00:21:42.530
it's something like this.

00:21:42.530 --> 00:21:44.650
two seconds afterwards, 10
seconds afterwards, a minute

00:21:44.650 --> 00:21:46.880
afterwards, five minutes
afterwards, 10 minutes

00:21:46.880 --> 00:21:52.030
afterwards, half an hour, two
hours, 12 hours, two days.

00:21:52.030 --> 00:21:53.830
Picture a ball floating
on top of water.

00:21:53.830 --> 00:21:56.630
And just as it's about to sink
below the surface, just as

00:21:56.630 --> 00:21:58.670
you're about to forget
something, pop it back up

00:21:58.670 --> 00:21:59.840
above the surface again.

00:21:59.840 --> 00:22:02.040
You do that seven or eight times
in this very particular

00:22:02.040 --> 00:22:03.630
sequence, you will
never forget it.

00:22:03.630 --> 00:22:05.840
That's how things are burned
into your brain.

00:22:05.840 --> 00:22:07.640
That's how our brains
are built.

00:22:07.640 --> 00:22:08.680
It's called the Spacing
Effect.

00:22:08.680 --> 00:22:09.750
And it's far more efficient.

00:22:09.750 --> 00:22:11.820
You could memorize something
only repeating it 10 or 11

00:22:11.820 --> 00:22:14.640
times instead of 1,000 times,
you might do it in a very

00:22:14.640 --> 00:22:16.090
compressed amount of time.

00:22:16.090 --> 00:22:18.230
So that's how you can
hack the code of

00:22:18.230 --> 00:22:20.240
your own brain's timing.

00:22:20.240 --> 00:22:22.550
And timing is just one example
of a whole bunch we have in

00:22:22.550 --> 00:22:25.990
the book about taking control of
timing, studying timing in

00:22:25.990 --> 00:22:29.150
yourself or your business or
your relationship and figuring

00:22:29.150 --> 00:22:30.760
out when is the best
time to do things.

00:22:30.760 --> 00:22:33.990
There a great story in the
book about a parole board

00:22:33.990 --> 00:22:36.830
where someone examined over the
course of the year whether

00:22:36.830 --> 00:22:39.650
or not this parole board was
likely or less likely to grant

00:22:39.650 --> 00:22:43.600
parole to criminals,
to inmates.

00:22:43.600 --> 00:22:46.170
And basically the results were
after lunch when they felt

00:22:46.170 --> 00:22:48.730
like going home, they granted
parole to everybody.

00:22:48.730 --> 00:22:50.720
The last thing in the world you
wanted to be was the first

00:22:50.720 --> 00:22:53.200
case they saw in the morning
when everybody was focused and

00:22:53.200 --> 00:22:54.700
really hard on the inmates.

00:22:54.700 --> 00:22:57.410
So all the lawyers who figured
this out made sure to schedule

00:22:57.410 --> 00:23:00.050
all of their hearings at the end
of the day, had a massive

00:23:00.050 --> 00:23:01.040
success rate.

00:23:01.040 --> 00:23:04.516
So timing is a really critical
factor in success.

00:23:04.516 --> 00:23:06.830
HUGH THOMPSON: I just noticed
that so many of your stories

00:23:06.830 --> 00:23:08.320
start in a bar.

00:23:08.320 --> 00:23:10.370
You could have easily said when
you meet somebody at a

00:23:10.370 --> 00:23:10.695
conference.

00:23:10.695 --> 00:23:12.290
BOB SULLIVAN: I am
an Irishman.

00:23:12.290 --> 00:23:14.570
HUGH THOMPSON: It's
just a side note.

00:23:14.570 --> 00:23:19.370
So the next element that we
found in plateaus have to do

00:23:19.370 --> 00:23:20.890
with flow issues.

00:23:20.890 --> 00:23:22.280
And we've got a couple
of different

00:23:22.280 --> 00:23:25.120
sections inside flow issues.

00:23:25.120 --> 00:23:28.640
One of the biggest causes
of problems with flow is

00:23:28.640 --> 00:23:30.230
something called erosion.

00:23:30.230 --> 00:23:34.140
Erosion is where you deplete
a resource over time.

00:23:34.140 --> 00:23:35.800
So I grew up in the Bahamas.

00:23:35.800 --> 00:23:37.160
Born and raised there.

00:23:37.160 --> 00:23:39.740
Wonderful place if anybody's
planning a vacation.

00:23:39.740 --> 00:23:41.920
We need your tourist dollars.

00:23:41.920 --> 00:23:45.770
But I used to go on a Easter
egg hunt every Easter.

00:23:45.770 --> 00:23:49.710
And it was on this isolated
island just set up for an

00:23:49.710 --> 00:23:50.800
Easter egg hunt.

00:23:50.800 --> 00:23:51.760
And it's amazing.

00:23:51.760 --> 00:23:55.260
As a 10-year-old, you'd find
half of the eggs that you'd

00:23:55.260 --> 00:23:58.080
find for the entire day in
the first five minutes.

00:23:58.080 --> 00:23:59.220
Because they are plentiful.

00:23:59.220 --> 00:24:00.500
They're everywhere.

00:24:00.500 --> 00:24:04.300
But as more kids start to find
more eggs, your rate of egg

00:24:04.300 --> 00:24:07.620
finding follows this
plateau curve.

00:24:07.620 --> 00:24:11.250
And it's interesting, any time
you're consuming a resource

00:24:11.250 --> 00:24:14.640
that is fixed, you hit
a plateau naturally.

00:24:14.640 --> 00:24:18.390
Because they're less and less
of those objects available.

00:24:18.390 --> 00:24:21.730
We also talk a lot about
step functions.

00:24:21.730 --> 00:24:26.080
So step functions are where you
have to make a big leap in

00:24:26.080 --> 00:24:27.140
a resource.

00:24:27.140 --> 00:24:28.950
Think about Cloud for example.

00:24:28.950 --> 00:24:31.480
Cloud has actually
solved the step

00:24:31.480 --> 00:24:33.440
function for many companies.

00:24:33.440 --> 00:24:37.260
Before, to move from the step of
not being in business on a

00:24:37.260 --> 00:24:39.860
web company to being in
business, you had to buy

00:24:39.860 --> 00:24:40.870
expensive servers.

00:24:40.870 --> 00:24:42.710
You had to house
them somewhere.

00:24:42.710 --> 00:24:45.060
You had to have somebody to
run and maintain them.

00:24:45.060 --> 00:24:48.160
The Cloud lets you take
spin up of VM, and

00:24:48.160 --> 00:24:50.090
you're going in seconds.

00:24:50.090 --> 00:24:54.990
And you can incrementally rent
capacity when you need it.

00:24:54.990 --> 00:24:58.490
It turns out that same function
of smoothing things

00:24:58.490 --> 00:25:00.980
is happening in other
areas of our lives.

00:25:00.980 --> 00:25:03.300
It's happening in car
rentals for example.

00:25:03.300 --> 00:25:03.960
Zipcar.

00:25:03.960 --> 00:25:06.040
I don't need something
for 24 hours.

00:25:06.040 --> 00:25:07.890
I just need it for an hour.

00:25:07.890 --> 00:25:12.280
And it gets into this bigger
issue of unused capacity.

00:25:12.280 --> 00:25:15.890
What unused capacity do
we have in our lives?

00:25:15.890 --> 00:25:16.910
Maybe you own a car.

00:25:16.910 --> 00:25:20.150
You drive it to work in the
morning at 9:00 AM and then

00:25:20.150 --> 00:25:21.730
you leave at 5:00 PM.

00:25:21.730 --> 00:25:24.860
What's happening to the car
between 9:00 and 5:00?

00:25:24.860 --> 00:25:26.180
It's just sitting there.

00:25:26.180 --> 00:25:29.300
If there was a way that you
could incrementally rent that

00:25:29.300 --> 00:25:33.110
car out to someone else and knew
it would be back at 5:00.

00:25:33.110 --> 00:25:35.170
You had all the right
insurances, all the right

00:25:35.170 --> 00:25:37.540
protection, you trusted
that person.

00:25:37.540 --> 00:25:38.150
You'd do it.

00:25:38.150 --> 00:25:40.530
It's a way to monetize
a fixed asset.

00:25:40.530 --> 00:25:44.270
And we're moving more and more
into this service economy

00:25:44.270 --> 00:25:46.110
where we're getting
out of steps,

00:25:46.110 --> 00:25:49.300
moving into smooth functions.

00:25:49.300 --> 00:25:51.260
Another area is a choke point.

00:25:51.260 --> 00:25:54.240
And a choke point, you can think
of it as the thing that

00:25:54.240 --> 00:25:55.530
fails first.

00:25:55.530 --> 00:25:59.510
So not to get too in depth here,
but how many people have

00:25:59.510 --> 00:26:02.160
followed some of the distributed
denial of service

00:26:02.160 --> 00:26:05.820
attacks against the financial
services institutions over

00:26:05.820 --> 00:26:07.470
these last 12 months?

00:26:07.470 --> 00:26:09.850
It's interesting to see
how many of these

00:26:09.850 --> 00:26:12.040
DDoS attacks go down.

00:26:12.040 --> 00:26:15.670
Before it just used to be
requests, essentially

00:26:15.670 --> 00:26:17.300
refreshing the page.

00:26:17.300 --> 00:26:20.980
Now a lot of the DDoS attacks
that we're seeing are

00:26:20.980 --> 00:26:22.580
application aware.

00:26:22.580 --> 00:26:25.940
They're actually trying to
stress out say the off system

00:26:25.940 --> 00:26:29.670
on the back end by being aware
of the page, actually entering

00:26:29.670 --> 00:26:32.970
characters into a user name
password field, and then

00:26:32.970 --> 00:26:35.840
causing the off to spin
on the back end

00:26:35.840 --> 00:26:37.025
instead of just the refresh.

00:26:37.025 --> 00:26:40.650
And the reason for that is that
back end system that's

00:26:40.650 --> 00:26:43.630
doing the authentication
is the choke point.

00:26:43.630 --> 00:26:46.590
It's the place that's likely
to fail first.

00:26:46.590 --> 00:26:49.610
And we're seeing attackers
become very aware that choke

00:26:49.610 --> 00:26:51.360
points exist in systems.

00:26:51.360 --> 00:26:53.760
And instead of going brute
force, they're more

00:26:53.760 --> 00:26:56.830
intelligent about how they
look for failures.

00:26:56.830 --> 00:27:00.270
So I want to talk about a choke
point that I'm sure is

00:27:00.270 --> 00:27:02.980
very near and dear
to your heart.

00:27:02.980 --> 00:27:05.010
And it's the CAPTCHA.

00:27:05.010 --> 00:27:08.270
So CAPTCHAs are a fascinating

00:27:08.270 --> 00:27:11.065
phenomenon of computer science.

00:27:11.065 --> 00:27:14.290
I've known Luis von Ahn for a
long time who was one of the

00:27:14.290 --> 00:27:15.970
creators of the CAPTCHA.

00:27:15.970 --> 00:27:19.280
And to me the CAPTCHA
is a choke point.

00:27:19.280 --> 00:27:21.990
Whenever I have to go into a
site, I get the user name and

00:27:21.990 --> 00:27:24.670
password wrong three or four
times, CAPTCHA comes up.

00:27:24.670 --> 00:27:25.830
I've got to type it in.

00:27:25.830 --> 00:27:29.310
They've gotten so complex now
that most of the time, I can't

00:27:29.310 --> 00:27:32.140
even figure out what they were
and have to go through two or

00:27:32.140 --> 00:27:33.410
three of them.

00:27:33.410 --> 00:27:36.235
But we often think about
CAPTCHAs from our perspective,

00:27:36.235 --> 00:27:39.710
but you never think about the
pain and turmoil this has

00:27:39.710 --> 00:27:43.640
caused for the bad guys, the
emotional disruption.

00:27:43.640 --> 00:27:47.430
So these guys had invested
a fortune in script

00:27:47.430 --> 00:27:50.910
infrastructure that went out and
bought all the tickets at

00:27:50.910 --> 00:27:53.320
Ticketmaster or went
out and created

00:27:53.320 --> 00:27:55.770
50,000 free email accounts.

00:27:55.770 --> 00:27:59.070
And suddenly one day when the
CAPTCHA was introduced, the

00:27:59.070 --> 00:28:00.560
scripts didn't work anymore.

00:28:00.560 --> 00:28:03.080
Because there was a test to
see if this person is a

00:28:03.080 --> 00:28:05.540
computer or are they a person?

00:28:05.540 --> 00:28:09.460
But it's interesting to see how
the security community and

00:28:09.460 --> 00:28:11.840
the hacking community,
in particular,

00:28:11.840 --> 00:28:13.700
responded to CAPTCHAs.

00:28:13.700 --> 00:28:15.440
The first thing that
they tried to do--

00:28:15.440 --> 00:28:18.140
I don't know if anybody
remembers this, but the very

00:28:18.140 --> 00:28:21.280
first thing was to try and
create optical character

00:28:21.280 --> 00:28:25.200
recognition software to
outwit the CAPTCHA.

00:28:25.200 --> 00:28:27.030
Couple big CAPTCHAs fell.

00:28:27.030 --> 00:28:29.500
But still CAPTCHAs got more
and more complex.

00:28:29.500 --> 00:28:31.810
So that didn't seem to
be a viable route.

00:28:31.810 --> 00:28:35.750
The next option was to hire
people in low average income

00:28:35.750 --> 00:28:38.210
countries to fill
out CAPTCHAs.

00:28:38.210 --> 00:28:38.610
Right.

00:28:38.610 --> 00:28:41.430
And even today, if anybody's
interested, afterwards come up

00:28:41.430 --> 00:28:43.820
to me, and I'll hook you up
to the right vendors.

00:28:43.820 --> 00:28:48.180
You can go on the weekend and
make a couple extra bucks by

00:28:48.180 --> 00:28:49.490
filling in CAPTCHAs.

00:28:49.490 --> 00:28:52.640
I think it's now up to 1/100
of a cent per CAPTCHA.

00:28:52.640 --> 00:28:54.690
So, again, if things
are tight here at

00:28:54.690 --> 00:28:57.530
Google, just let me know.

00:28:57.530 --> 00:28:59.050
But even that doesn't scale.

00:28:59.050 --> 00:29:03.320
If you have to try 100,000
password attempts, for

00:29:03.320 --> 00:29:05.465
example, that gets kind
of expensive.

00:29:05.465 --> 00:29:08.590
You might as well buy a stolen
credit card number for that

00:29:08.590 --> 00:29:09.980
investment.

00:29:09.980 --> 00:29:14.190
But then they did something
truly revolutionary to get rid

00:29:14.190 --> 00:29:17.020
of the choke point
of the CAPTCHA.

00:29:17.020 --> 00:29:19.340
They leveraged the
most powerful

00:29:19.340 --> 00:29:21.180
force on the internet.

00:29:21.180 --> 00:29:27.330
The force that included
image tags in HTML.

00:29:27.330 --> 00:29:31.280
The force that pushed the
balance of database search and

00:29:31.280 --> 00:29:32.840
access time.

00:29:32.840 --> 00:29:37.270
The force that picked
VHS over Betamax.

00:29:37.270 --> 00:29:39.010
Pornography.

00:29:39.010 --> 00:29:42.880
So they created pornographic
servers, most of the time

00:29:42.880 --> 00:29:45.270
specialty pornographic
servers.

00:29:45.270 --> 00:29:48.160
And to get to the next image or
next video, you didn't have

00:29:48.160 --> 00:29:51.460
to sign up, no credit
card required.

00:29:51.460 --> 00:29:55.800
All you had to do was fill
in five CAPTCHAs.

00:29:55.800 --> 00:29:56.790
That's it.

00:29:56.790 --> 00:29:58.130
Probably very quickly.

00:29:58.130 --> 00:29:58.820
That's my guess.

00:29:58.820 --> 00:30:00.040
I don't know.

00:30:00.040 --> 00:30:01.060
This is all theoretical.

00:30:01.060 --> 00:30:03.500
But it's interesting.

00:30:03.500 --> 00:30:06.110
Because they were getting
thousands of these things

00:30:06.110 --> 00:30:09.220
filled out for free every
single minute.

00:30:09.220 --> 00:30:12.860
It's a pretty sad commentary
on society actually.

00:30:12.860 --> 00:30:17.320
But this was a solution to the
choke point problem that

00:30:17.320 --> 00:30:18.590
really scaled.

00:30:18.590 --> 00:30:18.870
Right.

00:30:18.870 --> 00:30:23.970
There is no CAPTCHA, even
RECAPTCHA can't get around

00:30:23.970 --> 00:30:28.480
this problem of a motivated
person filling in CAPTCHAs.

00:30:28.480 --> 00:30:32.580
And what they would do is take
these CAPTCHAs real time from

00:30:32.580 --> 00:30:35.580
the sites that they were
trying to get into.

00:30:35.580 --> 00:30:38.410
And so they had this elaborate
infrastructure on how they

00:30:38.410 --> 00:30:40.040
delivered the CAPTCHAs
so it was in the

00:30:40.040 --> 00:30:41.790
right window of time.

00:30:41.790 --> 00:30:43.590
Truly, truly amazing.

00:30:43.590 --> 00:30:46.420
So that's one of our
inspirations in the book.

00:30:46.420 --> 00:30:47.820
If that can be an inspiration.

00:30:47.820 --> 00:30:50.880
And this is a less ambitious--

00:30:50.880 --> 00:30:53.335
this wasn't like five CAPTCHAs
for the next image.

00:30:53.335 --> 00:30:55.600
This was one CAPTCHA
per article

00:30:55.600 --> 00:30:57.030
of clothing or something.

00:30:57.030 --> 00:30:58.380
Appropriately censored.

00:30:58.380 --> 00:31:00.030
Appropriately censored.

00:31:00.030 --> 00:31:02.380
BOB SULLIVAN: Specialized
pornographic servers?

00:31:02.380 --> 00:31:05.990
HUGH THOMPSON: That's what
